      "side": 1,
      "message": "A couple of suggestions, feel free to ignore both.\n\n1. Consider defining type aliases to make these dictionaries more self documenting, e.g.\n\n  type TaskName \u003d string;\n\n2. Consider using the Map[1] object so you can use the above type alias as a key (e.g. const taskDims \u003d new Map\u003cTaskName, string[]\u003e()). The TypeScript compiler only allows \"string\" and \"number\" as the types for index signature parameters (e.g. {[key:TaskName]:string[]} will produce a compiler error, see TS1023). \n\nAn extra benefit of Map is that its forEach[2] method is slightly easier to read than Object.keys() and Object.values(), and it iterates all entries in insertion order, which might come in handy here.\n\n[1] https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Map\n[2] https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Map/forEach",
